description:
Gawkish, nerdy and nebbishy, Ferdie is Suzie’s best friend and confidante. Acting very much like the platonic male friends in the Doris Day movies of yore up through the lovable sitcom characters of today like Kenneth on “30 Rock,” Ferdie is constantly doing “damage control.” Whether covering for Suzie so yet another boss doesn’t fire her, or doing his best to clear up a misunderstanding Suzie’s flightiness has caused for one of her beleaguered boyfriends, Ferdie is always there to help.

Ferdie was the primary suitor to Suzie in Suzie Comics and other Archie/MLJ magazines. He was a gangly, awkward young man who could match Suzie for clumsiness. As the series progressed Ferdie to on more of a major role in the stories and became Suzie's permanent boyfriend. By the end of the original run with Suzie Comics #100, he was arguably the real star with Suzie more of a supporting character in her own book reduced to the status of the love interest and, bizarrely enough, the Straight Man.

issue_credits.name: Painting Pictures Is A Wonderful Hobby

name: Ferdie

description: Gregory Van Dripp evolved out of a character originally called Gregory Von Lingrinkiss the 3rd. He is an obnoxious mix of Veronica Lodge, sharing her trademark wealth, and Reggie Mantle, sharing his trademark vanity. A weasel when it comes to women, Gregory uses his wealth and charm to attract the fairer sex… and his shifty cunning to keep his competition at bay. Of course, good-natured Suzie longs to see the positive in everyone, and can’t see through Gregory’s smarmy disguise. Thankfully, her good friend Ferdie helps her see the light about this roguish Romeo.
name: Gregory Van Lingrinkiss III

deck: Marie Louise was an Austrian archduchess and thus Duchess of Parma from 1814 until her death. She was Napoleon's second wife and Empress of the French from 1810 to 1814.
description:
Origin

The end of the war between Austria and England against France and Bavaria (a part of the later Germany) resulted in the marriage of Napoleon Bonaparte and Marie Louise in 1810. This resulted in a period of peace and friendship between Austria and France. Marie Louise resented the French, but obediently agreed to the marriage. However, she was adored by Napoleon, whom she bore a son, who later became Napoleon II.

deck: The first wife of Napoleon Bonaparte, and thus the first Empress of the French.
description:
Origin

In 1804, Joséphine married Napoleon Bonaparte, becoming his first wife. It was her second marriage; her first husband died under the guillotine. Her children from her first marriage became important in European history. Her son Eugène was the grandfather of later Swedish and Danish kings and queens. The reigning houses of Belgium, Norway and Luxembourg also descend from her. She was divorced from Napoleon in 1810, after she did not bear him any children.
